Weibull Gaps Simulation

Lacey Etzkorn

2/2/2020

Model Formulation

$$

\[\begin{align} && \textbf{EM Algorithm} && \textbf{Frailty Pack} &&& \textbf{Difference} \\ &\text{Frailty} & w_i \sim N(0,\sigma^2) && \exp(v_i) \sim LN(1,\theta) &&& \text{Frailties are centered around different constants.} \\ &&&&&&& v_i \sim N(-\sigma^2/2, \sigma^2), \sigma^2 = \ln(\theta + 1) \Rightarrow w_i = v_i + \sigma^2/2 \\ &\text{Density} & f(y) = b_i k y^{k-1} \exp( - b_i \cdot y^k) && f(y) = h_i^{-k} k y^{k-1} \exp( - h_i^{-k} \cdot y^k) &&& b_i = h_i^{-k} \\ \\ & \text{Hazard} & \lambda(y) = b_i k y^{k-1} && \lambda(y) = h_i^{-k} k y^{k-1} \\ \\ &\text{Survivor} &S(y) = \exp( - b_i \cdot y^k) &&S(y)= \exp( - h_i^{-k} \cdot y^k) \\ \\ &\text{R. Predictor} & b_{xi} = \exp(X_i \beta_x + w_i) && h_{ix}^{-k} = \exp(X_i \beta_x + \ln(v_i)) &&& \text{Interpretation of }\beta_{x0} \text{ will vary. } \beta_{EMx0} \approx \beta_{FPx0} - \sigma^2/2 \\ \\ &\text{T. Predictor} & b_{yi} = \exp(X_i \beta_y + \alpha w_i) && h_{yi}^{-k_y} = \exp(X_i \beta_y + \alpha \ln(v_i)) &&& \text{Interpretation of }\beta_{y0} \text{ will vary. } \beta_{EMy0} \approx \beta_{FPy0} - \alpha \sigma^2/2 \\ \\ \end{align}\]

$$

Generate Parameter Grid

Here we create a grid of parameter values over which to simulate data. For now, we only generate one simulated data set per parameter combination.

par.grid <- 
expand.grid(beta.d0 = c(0, .1), beta.dtrt = c(0, .25), 
    beta.x0 = c(.5, 1), beta.xtrt = c(0, .25),
                   kd = c(1, 1.5), kx = c(1, 1.5), theta = c(.05, .1), alpha = c(0, 1))
truth <- par.grid %>%
gather("par", "truth") %>% distinct

Generate Data Sets and Fit Models

if(!file.exists("simulation_frame_021829.rdata")){
    # generate simulated data set for each parameter combination
    d <- par.grid %>%
    mutate(i = 1:n()) %>%
    nest(-i) %>%
    rename(parameters = data) %>%
    mutate(simulated.data = map(parameters, ~simulate.data(par0 = unlist(.), n = 200, frailty.center = "hazard")))
    
    # fit model on each of the data sets
    d$model = map(d$simulated.data, 
          ~weibull.gap.model(data = ., covar.names = "trt", 
                   e.iter = 400, m.iter = 1, frailty.center = "hazard"))
    d$model.linear = map(d$simulated.data, 
          ~weibull.gap.model(data = ., covar.names = "trt", 
                   e.iter = 400, m.iter = 1, frailty.center = "linear"))
    #d$model = map(d$model, 
    #     ~weibull.gap.model(add = T, model = ., covar.names = "trt", 
    #              e.iter = 200, m.iter = 1, frailty.center = "hazard"))

    # fit frailtypack on each data set
    d$frailtypack = map(d$simulated.data, 
    ~frailtypack::frailtyPenal(
        data = ., 
        formula = Surv(g, event) ~ trt + cluster(id) + terminal(terminal),
        formula.terminalEvent = ~ trt,
        hazard = "Weibull",
        recurrentAG = F,
        RandDist = "LogN",
        print.times = F))
    
    save(d, file = "simulation_frame_021829.rdata")
}else load(file = "simulation_frame_021829.rdata")

The column correct gives the proportion of confidence intervals containing the true value of the parameter. We see that our confidence intervals for alpha and theta do not contain nearly 95% of the observations. It is unclear whether this is a problem with the asymptotic assumption (we are only using 200 individuals per data set) or true bias in the MLE.

Set Different Starting Values

The model DOES run when I set starting values for the regression coefficients.

frailtyPenal(data = d$simulated.data[[min(which(d$fp.fail))]], 
        formula = Surv(g, event) ~ trt + cluster(id) + terminal(terminal),
        formula.terminalEvent = ~ trt,
        hazard = "Weibull",
        recurrentAG = F,
        RandDist = "LogN",
        print.times = F, init.B = c(0,0.25))

Compare Random Effect Estimates

if(!file.exists("Frailty_Center_Comparison_021020.rdata")){
    par0 = unlist(d$parameters[[1]])
    df1 <- simulate.data(par0 = par0, n = 200)
    df1 <- expected.frailty(df = df1, phi = par0, 
            f.w = list(Ew = function(w, phi) w), covar.names = "trt", frailty.center = "linear")
    df2 <- expected.frailty(df = df1, phi = par0, 
            f.w = list(Ew = function(w, phi) w), covar.names = "trt", frailty.center = "hazard")
    test <- weibull.gap.model(data = df1, covar.names = "trt",e.iter = 300, m.iter = 1, frailty.center = "linear")
    test2 <- weibull.gap.model(data = df1, covar.names = "trt",e.iter = 300, m.iter = 1, frailty.center = "hazard")
    save(par0, df1, df2, test, test2, file = "Frailty_Center_Comparison_021020.rdata")
}else load("Frailty_Center_Comparison_021020.rdata")
ggplot() +
geom_point(aes(x = df1$Ew, y = df2$Ew)) +
geom_point(aes(x = df1$Ew, y = df2$Ew + test2$estimates["theta"]/2), color = "red") +
geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0, color = "red") +
xlab("Frailty Estimate, Mu = 0 Assumption")+
ylab("Frailty Estimate, Mu = -Theta/2 Assumption") +
ggtitle("Frailty Estimates under two different Normality Assumptions, True Parameters")

We see that the estimated frailties (given the true parameters) are nearly exactly the same under the two different normality assumptions, except perhaps a constant shift. This is because the frailties are being penalized toward different constants. We can also see that the empirical variance of the frailties are nearly the same:

var(df1$Ew); var(df2$Ew); var(df1$w)
